Also ‚Ä¶ modern P&I (Marine) shipping insurance traces back to the 16th century in Italy (Genoa). 

Through The last ~400 years, these rates have been the motivating factors for send the marines to the Barbary Coast (‚ÄúThe shores of Tripoli‚Äù) around 1800 to fight piracy, to the blockade of the South by the Union Navy in the Civil War to Lend Lease in the North Atlantic in WW2.

Nothing ever ‚Äúcloses.‚Äù Shipping is all about economics (as it is a commercial enterprise). And when the risk causes the insurance rates to skyrocket above the benefits of shipping, cargo stops moving.

So, the explanation of what ‚Äúcloses‚Äù the Strait of Hormuz is a 400 year old story.

Closing Hormuz is not as much a factor in Iran launching attacks on ships. Instead, it is how shipping companies and insurance companies react.  

1Ô∏è‚É£ We have the ongoing example of the Houthis in the Red Sea.  Over a hundred ships have been attacked; two have been sunk and four mariners killed.  The reason that 40% of ships have diverted is due to the high WAR RISK insurance.  
2Ô∏è‚É£ We have the past example of the Iran-Iraq/Tanker War from 1981 to 1988 where over 450 ships were attacked.  That conflict did not see cargo stop, but there was a spike in WAR RISK.  It should be noted that large crude oil tankers are of lower value and cost than large containerships that need to transit the Red Sea.
3Ô∏è‚É£ As there is no large-scale alternative to the Strait of Hormuz to exit the Persian Gulf, it is unlikely that global navies (China, India, Japan, and Korea) will tolerate a prolonged closure.

eia.gov/todayinenergy/detail‚Ä¶

How does the Strait of Hormuz ‚Äúclose?‚Äù

Insurance rates. The P&I (Protection and Indemnity) clubs that offer marine insurance will set the coverage rates and the shippers will have to decide of it is worth the risk.

It never really closes, it‚Äôs about the all-in price to ship.
